Sure, here is a simple Python function that checks if a number is prime:

```python
def is_prime(n):
    if n <= 1:
        return False
    elif n <= 3:
        return True
    elif n % 2 == 0 or n % 3 == 0:
        return False
    i = 5
    while i * i <= n:
        if n % i == 0 or n % (i + 2) == 0:
            return False
        i += 6
    return True
```

This function works by first checking if the number is less than or equal to 1, in which case it returns `False` because 1 and all negative numbers are not prime. It then checks if the number is less than or equal to 3, in which case it returns `True` because 2 and 3 are prime. Then it checks if the number is divisible by 2 or 3. If it is, it returns `False` because it is not prime. After that, it starts checking divisibility from 5 up to the square root of the number (since a larger factor of the number would be a multiple of smaller factor that has already been checked). It checks divisibility by 6k ± 1, which covers all possible prime numbers since all primes are of the form 6k ± 1, for some integer k, except for 2 and 3. If the number is divisible by any of these, it returns `False`. If the number is not divisible by any of these, it is prime and the function returns `True`.

Certainly! Generating a table of contents (TOC) automatically in a LaTeX document is a straightforward process. LaTeX uses the `\tableofcontents` command to generate a table of contents based on the document's sectioning commands (`\chapter`, `\section`, `\subsection`, etc.). The first time this command is used, LaTeX will not include entries for sections on pages prior to the point the command is issued. Subsequent uses will update the TOC.

Here's an example of how to generate a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document:

```latex
\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{hyperref} % Optional, for hyperlinks in the TOC

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % Generate the TOC

\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Background}
This is the background section.

\section{Objectives}
These are the objectives of the document.

\chapter{Theoretical Framework}
\section{First Section}
This is the first section of the theoretical framework.

\section{Second Section}
This is the second section of the theoretical framework.

\chapter{Methodology}
\section{Procedure}
The procedure followed in the study.

\section{Data Analysis}
How data was analyzed.

\end{document}
```

Explanation of the commands and their effects:

- `\documentclass{book}`: This sets the document class to `book`, which is a standard class for large documents. Other options include `article`, `report`, and `letter`.

- `\usepackage{hyperref}`: This is an optional line that adds hyperlinks to the table of contents. It's not necessary for the TOC to be generated but is useful for documents that will be read on screen.

- `\tableofcontents`: This command generates the table of contents. The first time it is used, it will not include entries for sections on pages prior to where the command is placed. Subsequent uses will update the TOC.

- `\chapter{Introduction}`, `\section{Background}`, etc.: These are the sectioning commands. LaTeX uses these to build the table of contents. The `\chapter` command creates a new chapter, and the `\section` command creates a new section within that chapter. The TOC will list all chapters and sections defined with these commands.

To compile the document and generate the table of contents, you would typically run LaTeX on the document twice. The first run will include the chapter and section titles in the TOC, but the page numbers will be placeholders. The second run will replace these placeholders with the correct page numbers. If you're using the `hyperref` package, you'll also get clickable links in the TOC.

